ce:section.ce:para:
To verify the reactive species in the photocatalytic system (Fig. 6
                        ), TEMP and DMPO were used to prove the existence of reactive radical species. Intensified signals of DMPO-OH (1:2:2:1) were observed in both the CDs/P25 and P25. However, the CDs/P25 contained higher intensity of hydroxyl radicals than the P25. Similarly, more monoclinic oxygen radicals and superoxide radicals were produced in the CDs/P25 than in the P25. Based on the above analysis, it can be concluded that the CDs/P25 could stimulate the radical and nonradical pathways in the degradation of HA, FA, and leachate. Under light exposure, the CDs/P25 would generate more photogenic electrons and holes, thus producing •O2
                        − and •OH radicals due to the reaction with O2 and H2O, respectively. As a result, the pollutants (i.e., HA, FA, and leachate) were attacked and degraded by the radical and nonradical pathways. Vatanpour et al., 2022) reported that the presence of CDs could enhance the degradation ability of HA. It was also noted that more hydroxyl radicals, monoclinic oxygen radicals, and superoxide radicals were generated in the HA. These results suggested that the CDs/P25 could transfer some large molecules of HA into smaller molecules than the P25.
